</script><tw-passagedata pid="1" name="introduction" tags="" position="133,162">The Himalayas by Katie.
I made this on twine for my school project.

[[more info]]</tw-passagedata><tw-passagedata pid="2" name="more info" tags="" position="423,406">Welcome to some of the worlds highest peaks!
You are an explorer and have come to investigate the himalayas.
To move around click on the blue words.
Your mission is to find everest.

Nearly 53 million people live in 5 different countries acros the himalayas; [[Nepal]], [[India]], [[Bangladesh]], [[China]] and [[Pakistan]].

￼&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.toffeemilkshake.co.uk/katie-twines/images/himalayan-city.jpg&quot;&gt;

As well as the worlds highest mountains some of the biggest rivers flow from the Himalayas: the Indus, the Ganges and the Tsangpo-Brahmaputra.

The Himalayas have a big effect on the climate of the region. They keep the monsoon rains on the Indian plain and limit rainfall on the Tibetan plateau.</tw-passagedata><tw-passagedata pid="3" name="India" tags="" position="604,533">The Indian Himalayan Region is the section of the Himalayas within India.

It starts from the foothills of the south and extends up to Tibetan plateau in the north.

Mighty old streams like the Indus, Sutlej, Kali, Kosi and Brahmaputra have cut through steep gorges to escape into the Great Plains.

￼The Himalays were formed 40 to 50 million years ago when India crashed into the Asian plate.

￼&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.toffeemilkshake.co.uk/katie-twines/images/Himalaya-formation.gif&quot;&gt;

From here you can get to [[China]] and [[Nepal]] in the north [[Bangladesh]] in the east and [[Pakistan]] in the west. </tw-passagedata><tw-passagedata pid="4" name="China" tags="" position="598,9">Pangong Tso is a lake which is spread across the border between India and China with an area of 700 km one of the worlds largest lakes.

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.toffeemilkshake.co.uk/katie-twines/images/Ladakh-Pangong-Lake.jpg&quot;&gt;

[[Pakistan]] is in the west. [[Bangladesh]], [[Nepal]] and [[India]] are in the south.</tw-passagedata><tw-passagedata pid="5" name="Pakistan" tags="" position="134,530">The Himalayas cross the border between India and Pakistan and reach their western end in the dramatic 8000 m peak of Nanga Parbat, which rises above the Indus valley and is the most westerly of the 8000 m summits.

&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.toffeemilkshake.co.uk/katie-twines/images/Nanga-Parbat.jpg&quot;&gt;

You can go to [[India]] and [[China]] in the east.</tw-passagedata><tw-passagedata pid="6" name="Bangladesh" tags="" position="786,266">The Ganges and the Brahmaputra meet in Bangladesh and drain into the Bay of Bengal through the world&#x27;s largest river delta, the Sunderbans.


￼&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.toffeemilkshake.co.uk/katie-twines/images/bangladesh.png&quot; width=&quot;500&quot;&gt;

You can go to [[Nepal]] in the Northwest. You can go to [[India]] in the west and you can go to [[China]] in the north.
</tw-passagedata><tw-passagedata pid="7" name="Nepal" tags="" position="604,161">Kathmandu is the capital of Nepal and the largest city in the Himalayas. 

East of the Kathmandu Valley lies valley of the Bhote/Sun Kosi river which rises in Tibet and provides the main overland route between Nepal and China.

Further east is the Mahalangur Himal with four of the world&#x27;s six highest mountains, including the highest: [[Mount Everest]].

￼&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.toffeemilkshake.co.uk/katie-twines/images/kathmandu-himalayas.jpg&quot;&gt;

You can get to [[China]] in the north [[India]] in the south and [[Bangladesh]] in the southeast.</tw-passagedata><tw-passagedata pid="8" name="Mount Everest" tags="" position="448,259">Congratulations! You have found Mount Everest.

With an 8,850 metre summit it is the tallest mountain in the world.

Molly Hughes is the youngest woman to climb Mount Everest and to climb both sides.

She climbed the south side in 2012 when she was 21 and the north side in 2017 at the age of 26.

Everest grows by half a centimeter every year.

The temperature can be -62 C.

In mid May each year, the jet stream moves north causing the winds the calm and temperatures to warm enough for people to try to summit. This is called the &#x27;summit window&#x27;.

Everest is called Chomolungma by the Tibetan people. It means mother goddess of the universe.

Like all mountains around the world the local indigenous people were the first to see it.

The wind can blow over 200 mph.

￼&lt;img src=&quot;http://www.toffeemilkshake.co.uk/katie-twines/images/everest.jpg&quot;&gt;</tw-passagedata></tw-storydata>

